<subSubSection pageId="19" pageNumber="20" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="19.[151,1437,578,1290]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,314,758,785]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Diagnosis</emphasis>
. Size medium, length 
<quantity box="[568,706,758,786]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.15" metricValueMax="3.5" metricValueMin="2.8" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" unit="mm" value="3.15" valueMax="3.5" valueMin="2.8">2.8–3.5 mm</quantity>
; dorsal ground color light to medium reddish brown with pattern of darker maculae (
<figureCitation box="[375,449,795,821]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–9" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1792,1817]" captionTargetBox="[354,1209,529,1746]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[346,1242,548,1765]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 1–9. Xanthonia species, dorsal habitus. 1) X. angulata (Bastrop Co., Texas); 2) X. dentata (Jeff Davis Co., Texas); 3) X. furcata (Wood Co., Texas); 4) X. nitida (Pecos Co., Texas); 5) X. parva (Kerr Co., Texas); 6) X. picturata (Robertson Co., Texas); 7) X. querci (Val Verde Co., Texas); 8) X. texana (Bandera Co., Texas); 9) X. villosula (Bossier Parish, Louisiana). Images to scale, scale bar = 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3414688" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3414688/files/figure.png" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Figs 3</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[465,497,795,821]" captionStart="FIGURES 76–78" captionStartId="16.[151,264,1320,1345]" captionTargetBox="[296,1319,474,1291]" captionTargetId="figure@16.[266,1322,474,1302]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="FIGURES 76–78. Xanthonia species, types and type labels. 76) X. texana; 77) X. querci; 78) X. furcata. Map 7. Distribution of Xanthonia texana." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3414704" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3414704/files/figure.png" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">78</figureCitation>
); venter of body dark brown to black; pubescence of elytra composed of reclined hairs on intervals in single rows and appressed hairs arising from punctures shorter than erect hairs; ventral tooth of profemur obsolete to absent; lateral margins of all ventrites entire; median lobe of male genitalia gradually tapered distally, apex with deep, acute v-shaped incision with acutely pointed lobe on each side (
<figureCitation box="[1143,1221,903,929]" captionStart="FIGURES 64–75" captionStartId="14.[151,264,1513,1538]" captionTargetBox="[189,1398,546,1494]" captionTargetId="figure@14.[189,1398,546,1494]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIGURES 64–75. Xanthonia species, en-face and lateral view of median lobe. 64) X. angulata (Washington, DC); 65–66) X. angulata (Mt. Vernon, Virginia); 67–68) (Bastrop State Park, Texas), 69); X. striata (Flatbush, New York); 70) X. striata (Nelson Co., Virginia); 71) X. striata (Wolfville, Maryland); 72–73) X. striata (Hanover, Pennsylvania); 74–75) X. furcata (Union Co., Illinois). All figures from Weisman (1960), except 67–68." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3414702" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3414702/files/figure.png" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Fig 74</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="19.[151,1437,578,1290]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,275,939,965]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Range</emphasis>
. Recorded from 
<collectingRegion box="[465,544,939,965]" country="United States of America" name="Illinois" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Illinois</collectingRegion>
and 
<collectingRegion box="[598,698,939,965]" country="United States of America" name="Missouri" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Missouri</collectingRegion>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Staines, C. L. &amp; Weisman, D. M." box="[712,1013,939,965]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" pagination="157 - 183" refId="ref15464" refString="Staines, C. L. &amp; Weisman, D. M. (2001 a) The species of Xanthonia Baly 1863 (Coleoptera: Chrysomelidae: Eumolpinae) in North America east of the Mississippi River. Proceedings of the Entomological Society of Washington, 103 (1), 157 - 183." type="journal article" year="2001">Staines &amp; Weisman 2001a</bibRefCitation>
). During the present study, specimens were recorded 
<collectingRegion box="[320,385,976,1002]" country="United States of America" name="Texas" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Texas</collectingRegion>
and adjacent 
<collectingRegion box="[543,660,975,1001]" country="United States of America" name="Oklahoma" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Oklahoma</collectingRegion>
(Appendix 10). In 
<collectingRegion box="[880,948,976,1002]" country="United States of America" name="Texas" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Texas</collectingRegion>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Staines &amp; Weisman" authorityYear="2001" box="[960,1073,975,1001]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Xanthonia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="furcata">
<emphasis box="[960,1073,975,1001]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">X. furcata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is known from the northeastern portion of the state (
<figureCitation box="[377,454,1011,1037]" captionStart="MAPS 1–6" captionStartId="18.[151,223,1804,1829]" captionTargetBox="[276,1314,323,1756]" captionTargetId="figure@18.[264,1323,330,1762]" captionText="MAPS 1–6. Distribution of Xanthonia species. 1) X. vagans; 2) X. furcata (■), X. marquai (♦), X. nitida (●); 3) X. hirsuta; 4) X. picturata; 5) X. angulata (♦), X. dentata (●), X. querci (■); 6) X. parva (■), X. villosula (●)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3448931" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3448931/files/figure.png" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Map 2</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="19.[151,1437,578,1290]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,411,1046,1073]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Plant associations</emphasis>
. The 
<typeStatus box="[472,570,1047,1073]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">holotype</typeStatus>
is labeled as having been taken on wild cherry. There are no plant associations for the 
<collectingRegion box="[232,297,1084,1110]" country="United States of America" name="Texas" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Texas</collectingRegion>
material, but the collection records from 
<collectingRegion box="[761,878,1083,1109]" country="United States of America" name="Oklahoma" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Oklahoma</collectingRegion>
are from oak.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="19.[151,1437,578,1290]" box="[199,1144,1118,1146]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,452,1118,1145]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Seasonal distribution</emphasis>
. Collections in 
<collectingRegion box="[629,694,1120,1146]" country="United States of America" name="Texas" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Texas</collectingRegion>
and 
<collectingRegion box="[748,865,1119,1145]" country="United States of America" name="Oklahoma" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Oklahoma</collectingRegion>
are from April and May.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="19" pageNumber="20" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="19.[151,1437,578,1290]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,308,1155,1181]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Remarks</emphasis>
. As with the preceding two species, this species can be tricky to identify without reference to the male genitalia, but its color pattern when well developed and its restricted range in 
<collectingRegion box="[1022,1087,1192,1218]" country="United States of America" name="Texas" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Texas</collectingRegion>
are helpful. The male genitalia with a deep and sharply defined v-shaped emargination and acute lateral lobes are highly diagnostic.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="19.[151,1437,578,1290]" box="[199,1388,1262,1290]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,447,1262,1289]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Specimens examined</emphasis>
. See Appendix 10. The male genitalia of 
<specimenCount box="[912,1012,1263,1289]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" type="male">14 males</specimenCount>
from 5 localities were examined.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
